1
00:00:01,026 --> 00:00:21,650
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa

2
00:00:22,423 --> 00:00:38,204
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa I thought tonight to

3
00:00:40,953 --> 00:01:05,069
sort of give a wide sweep to our meditation practice, see if I can put it in some sort of context, beginning perhaps with the Buddha's own experience, and then this crucial teaching of the wheel of dependent origination, his understanding of where our peculiar delusion lies,

4
00:01:06,602 --> 00:01:13,174
And then finally at the end, hopefully, a little bit about these problems we come across when we're sitting, these hindrances.

5
00:01:17,460 --> 00:01:26,956
So the Buddha himself is the sort of basic paradigm, he's the archetype of this particular path, that's what he stands for.

6
00:01:28,573 --> 00:01:37,328
And his early life is meant to be full of pleasure, easygoing, loving family, all that sort of stuff, everything that people dream about these days.

7
00:01:38,670 --> 00:01:45,299
And around about his early 20s, middle 20s, something happened and he got fed up with it.

8
00:01:46,242 --> 00:01:51,790
And what we can say is that he went through what we would now call a sort of existential crisis.

9
00:01:52,331 --> 00:01:53,974
He wondered why he was alive.

10
00:01:54,635 --> 00:01:56,337
In his terms, why he suffered.

11
00:01:57,459 --> 00:02:09,937
In the mythology surrounding that psychological event, we have this business of him being out hunting or wandering around the countryside or something.

12
00:02:09,918 --> 00:02:12,580
when he comes across three different types of people.

13
00:02:12,721 --> 00:02:16,866
One is very sick, one's very old, and one's dead.

14
00:02:17,747 --> 00:02:23,554
And each time it comes as a surprise to him because previously he'd been shielded from this by his family.

15
00:02:24,354 --> 00:02:32,283
So we can take this as a metaphor for the fact that not until our early 20s do we really have an inkling of what death might be.

16
00:02:32,343 --> 00:02:38,811
It's the stirrings of a future middle-aged crisis, we can say.

17
00:02:42,031 --> 00:02:43,552
and the following old age crisis.

18
00:02:44,996 --> 00:02:51,926
So he's now asking about these three things, sickness, old age and death.

19
00:02:53,770 --> 00:02:55,673
Does every human being suffer from this?

20
00:02:56,052 --> 00:02:57,155
Do I suffer from this?

21
00:02:57,415 --> 00:03:09,675
And it was this recognition that the end of life normally ends with some sort of sickness, some sort of what my father called the decrepitude of old age, and death.

22
00:03:09,655 --> 00:03:26,353
And of course it makes nonsense of trying to live a life around pleasure, riches, fame and anything else which is going to come to an end because fundamentally what we want is something which is going to last, some everlasting state.

23
00:03:28,955 --> 00:03:37,705
So there was a movement during his time, it had begun before, this business of leaving home and becoming an ascetic.

24
00:03:38,191 --> 00:03:42,495
It tended to be anti-establishment.

25
00:03:44,316 --> 00:03:50,181
The establishment was the Brahminical tradition, which eventually developed in what we now know as Hinduism.

26
00:03:50,901 --> 00:03:57,087
And they did have their ascetics, but there were new teachers came along who said quite radically different things.

27
00:03:57,769 --> 00:04:01,532
One of them was what we would call now an absolute materialist.

28
00:04:01,771 --> 00:04:06,156
You know, you just have the body, and there was the brain, and when you died, that was the end of it.

29
00:04:06,135 --> 00:04:16,531
There were some people with strange ideas about karma, some sort of predestination that you had to run the gauntlet of karma.

30
00:04:16,932 --> 00:04:26,848
So from being born a bug, you then had to go right through to a rat, to a cow, to a human being, and onwards until the process just naturally came to an end.

31
00:04:27,288 --> 00:04:28,971
And there was nothing you do about it.

32
00:04:28,951 --> 00:04:42,709
So, like this person said, if you went up one side of the Ganges, slaughtering and pillaging and doing all sorts of rubbish, it wouldn't have any effect at all on this predestined path.

33
00:04:42,730 --> 00:04:49,418
And if you came down the other side and did great acts of compassion and wonderful acts of love, it would make no difference whatsoever.

34
00:04:49,459 --> 00:04:50,841
It was completely predestined.

35
00:04:52,559 --> 00:05:05,132
So within that sort of atmosphere the Buddha began his training and he began his training with what you might call the conservative orthodox line of Brahmanism.

36
00:05:05,593 --> 00:05:16,845
He went to two teachers who basically taught him very ancient techniques of meditation which were about gaining very highly ecstatic states of mind.

37
00:05:18,867 --> 00:05:26,682
And whenever he achieved this, to the satisfaction of the teacher, the teacher would acclaim him as equal to them, these two teachers, and then invite him to teach.

38
00:05:26,742 --> 00:05:33,495
But both times, he refused the appointment and said that it hadn't completely satisfied him.

39
00:05:33,516 --> 00:05:41,331
He hadn't really got to the end of suffering because whenever he came out of these states, he was as bad as he was before.

40
00:05:41,665 --> 00:05:43,367
There wasn't any particular improvement.

41
00:05:44,529 --> 00:05:52,043
So he then went on to a second type of training that was very common in those days, and that was what we now term self-mortification.

42
00:05:54,608 --> 00:06:03,184
So whereas the, shall we say, the worldly life, the materialist life,

43
00:06:03,281 --> 00:06:20,937
presumes that you can get happiness, you know, through the ordinary gifts that we get through living, TVs and stuff like that, and perhaps there's a sort of stoicism there that, well, you know, you can't be perfectly happy, that sort of attitude.

44
00:06:22,218 --> 00:06:32,326
The meditative school that he went to said that real happiness wasn't to do with the material world, it was mental.

45
00:06:32,880 --> 00:06:35,346
So you could create these beautiful mental states, you see.

46
00:06:35,786 --> 00:06:39,954
So even here, in our vipassana meditation, sometimes beautiful states do arise, correct?

47
00:06:40,514 --> 00:06:40,875
Definitely.

48
00:06:41,396 --> 00:06:48,509
And we can presume that this is nirvana, this is actually where we're really aiming for, if we could just maintain it, you see.

49
00:06:49,807 --> 00:06:57,661
The next school said that, in a sense, what was wrong was the body itself.

50
00:06:57,742 --> 00:06:59,985
Somehow you had to free yourself from the body.

51
00:07:00,627 --> 00:07:05,516
So self-mortification exercises were to do with subduing the body.

52
00:07:06,117 --> 00:07:10,464
And the most common was just to starve it, was to eat very little.

53
00:07:11,608 --> 00:07:18,483
Now those of you who've done something like a 10-day fast, a water fast, will know that the first three days, just like a retreat, are horrible.

54
00:07:19,043 --> 00:07:27,442
And then somehow the body has cleared a lot of its toxins and you can feel quite lovely within the body.

55
00:07:28,423 --> 00:07:32,031
Except, of course, that the body is now eating itself.

56
00:07:32,399 --> 00:07:35,341
So you can't go on like that for too long.

57
00:07:35,362 --> 00:07:42,110
So they reduced their intake to a minimum, and he says of himself that he came to a point where he could hold his spine through his stomach.

58
00:07:42,829 --> 00:07:45,353
That gives you an idea of how thin he got.

59
00:07:45,372 --> 00:07:47,396
But this led him nowhere either.

60
00:07:48,196 --> 00:08:00,550
So in desperation, he was by himself sitting on a road, probably looking fairly disconsolate when a woman passed by with, it seems, a bowl of rice pudding to offer to a particular deity in a shrine.

61
00:08:00,529 --> 00:08:03,497
But seeing him in such a miserable state, offered it to him.

62
00:08:04,238 --> 00:08:06,805
Actually, the commentaries bump it up a bit.

63
00:08:07,245 --> 00:08:11,677
They say that she thought he was a deity and therefore offered it to him.

64
00:08:13,600 --> 00:08:16,007
I can't really imagine him looking like a deity.

65
00:08:16,274 --> 00:08:30,271
Anyway, this rice pudding, you see, gave him a certain energy, which he'd been lacking through this self-mortification exercise, and it brought up a certain hope in him, and he must have been recollecting his own spiritual journey.

66
00:08:31,432 --> 00:08:45,149
And he remembered this point in childhood, probably around about the age of eight, something like that, eight, nine, ten, when he's watching his father doing the ceremonial first ploughing of the season.

67
00:08:47,408 --> 00:08:57,660
And that state he recalled as being somehow different from all the mental stuff, from all the states that he'd achieved through these meditations.

68
00:08:59,102 --> 00:09:00,825
It was a very concentrated state.

69
00:09:03,048 --> 00:09:07,754
In the commentaries it says it's a sort of jhana.

70
00:09:08,335 --> 00:09:16,284
But something different had been about that state, which he recognized as having...

71
00:09:17,480 --> 00:09:20,364
some sort of investigative, some sort of curiosity.

72
00:09:21,586 --> 00:09:41,495
Now, the image, when I want to describe to people what this satipanya, this awareness with intuitive wisdom is like, the closest I can get to in terms of an image is of a little child round about the beginning of language,

73
00:09:42,909 --> 00:09:48,660
where there's no great conceptual thinking, where they see something like a little bug, which they've never seen before.

74
00:09:50,024 --> 00:09:51,967
And they become entranced, don't they?

75
00:09:51,988 --> 00:09:54,432
They become sort of totally bewitched by it.

76
00:09:54,793 --> 00:09:55,634
They just look at it.

77
00:09:55,916 --> 00:09:56,517
You can see them.

78
00:09:56,537 --> 00:09:58,640
They're just locked onto the object.

79
00:09:58,991 --> 00:10:04,801
And they're watching intently, and even so that the mouth drops, the jaw drops.

80
00:10:05,422 --> 00:10:18,743
Now, one of the things about the posture is that, especially in Zen, because Zen is very good at describing posture, they always say that the lips are together but the teeth are apart.

81
00:10:20,105 --> 00:10:22,148
So when your teeth are apart, your jaw is relaxed.

82
00:10:23,443 --> 00:10:30,905
In your meditation, if you watch, whenever you're thinking, you may feel very small little movements on your tongue.

83
00:10:32,235 --> 00:10:37,803
Because the thoughts always are connected to the tongue, just as a natural thing, because of speech.

84
00:10:38,644 --> 00:10:43,071
And any tension about thinking or whatnot immediately brings in the jaw, you see.

85
00:10:43,991 --> 00:10:51,663
So sometimes in your meditation, even by concentrating on your tongue and on the relaxation of the jaw, you can find that your thoughts stop.

86
00:10:51,982 --> 00:10:56,469
Your thoughts at least are calmed.

87
00:10:56,489 --> 00:10:57,770
So...

88
00:10:59,741 --> 00:11:09,553
That moment when a child just looks at something with that open curiosity, see, a child's not coming to that experience with a concept.

89
00:11:10,534 --> 00:11:14,759
And while it's there with the experience, it hasn't got conceptual thinking to think about it.

90
00:11:15,280 --> 00:11:18,725
So all it can do is just purely absorb directly what's going on.

91
00:11:19,166 --> 00:11:22,089
It's only then, after a certain time, will it turn around and ask what it is.

92
00:11:22,629 --> 00:11:23,691
What is that?

93
00:11:25,173 --> 00:11:54,994
so trying to get back to that pure inquisitive without a verbal question consciousness that's what we're trying to do that's the aim of the practice and what we're doing is we're trying to lift that consciousness out of its confusion with confusion it's blending with

94
00:11:55,682 --> 00:12:00,629
everything that we experience in the body as feelings, in the heart, and in thoughts.

95
00:12:03,594 --> 00:12:17,934
So now the Buddha went to sit, and in a sense he was at the end of his tether, so he made this rather remarkable determination that he wouldn't move, he wouldn't shift from the seat until he was fully enlightened, or he'd die.

96
00:12:18,696 --> 00:12:18,855
See?

97
00:12:20,357 --> 00:12:20,778
And

98
00:12:22,294 --> 00:12:23,416
I don't know whether you've tried that.

99
00:12:23,936 --> 00:12:27,740
It doesn't last very long for me anyway.

100
00:12:29,600 --> 00:12:31,003
It's a sort of one too many.

101
00:12:32,144 --> 00:12:34,466
But anyway, that was his determination and he just sat there.

102
00:12:35,326 --> 00:12:41,030
Luckily for him and for us of course, he made the breakthrough and he came to this understanding.

103
00:12:41,831 --> 00:12:50,799
Now this understanding, he then, it's said, that he then spent the first night going through the psychological understanding of what he'd experienced.

104
00:12:51,876 --> 00:12:53,599
to show how suffering arises.

105
00:12:53,620 --> 00:12:57,404
Then he went through the next night the other way, to show how it came to an end.

106
00:12:58,005 --> 00:13:01,870
And then, in the third night, he recapitulated and, as it were, did them both.

107
00:13:02,591 --> 00:13:10,003
So this is just a way, really, again, of saying that when the Enlightenment came, when he actually...

108
00:13:09,982 --> 00:13:24,643
realize the way things really are, it took a while for this whole thing to work out in terms of how to teach it in sort of looking at the human being from the point of view of the enlightened person.

109
00:13:26,586 --> 00:13:30,912
Now one thing that I've come across

110
00:13:32,511 --> 00:14:00,408
having been in the East and then coming back to the West in the East always hearing, shall we say, the paradigm about the human being from the Buddhist point of view and therefore as it were going through a spate of years where I'm out of touch with things like psychodynamic theory and stuff like that coming back to the West I began to realize that the way we look at things is from a different angle

111
00:14:00,389 --> 00:14:15,427
And this has come up quite sharply since I've been down at Gaia House, where that area around Totnes and Dartington and all that is a sort of hotbed of alternative stuff.

112
00:14:16,623 --> 00:14:25,150
So I've got myself a really bad name as being anti-psychotherapy and all that sort of stuff.

113
00:14:25,171 --> 00:14:27,011
But I didn't actually mean to do that.

114
00:14:27,972 --> 00:14:46,629
What I was trying to do was try and make very clear to people that if you want to become enlightened, if you want to actually be liberated from suffering from the Buddha's point of view, then you've really got to understand the psychology as the Buddha understood it.

115
00:14:46,610 --> 00:14:57,769
So this takes us now into this weed of dependence origination which we talked a little bit about this morning and during the day.

116
00:14:57,808 --> 00:15:08,187
And the fundamental stance of the Buddha, what he came to understand was that that fundament, the problem was ignorance.

117
00:15:08,206 --> 00:15:11,351
Now this ignorance is not culpable.

118
00:15:11,450 --> 00:15:13,032
We're not blameworthy.

119
00:15:13,392 --> 00:15:15,614
It's a simple existential state.

120
00:15:15,654 --> 00:15:16,274
We don't know.

121
00:15:16,294 --> 00:15:23,423
So, not worrying about whether we have a past life or a future life, but just taking this life.

122
00:15:24,004 --> 00:15:30,591
Consider, in Buddhist understanding, the mind and consciousness arise with conception.

123
00:15:31,751 --> 00:15:34,695
So that is what consciousness is actually experiencing.

124
00:15:35,054 --> 00:15:39,279
Just being in a cellular life, in a very material base.

125
00:15:39,664 --> 00:15:47,259
And it's only later, as the fetus grows, that it begins to get some sort of messages about feeling, touch, hearing, things like that.

126
00:15:48,100 --> 00:15:54,072
When it's born, then of course we open our eyes, light comes in, we begin to hear things, we begin to understand things.

127
00:15:54,471 --> 00:16:02,888
And all this is, as it were, coming into a consciousness which has begun from a position of not knowing.

128
00:16:03,408 --> 00:16:31,677
so that not knowing now makes a mistake which is quite understandable it presumes itself to be what it finds itself in I am the body I am these feelings I am what I think I think therefore I am see it comes all the way up to the highest of philosophers so you can understand that that's a very I mean what else could consciousness do it doesn't it doesn't have another another it doesn't have a choice

129
00:16:33,832 --> 00:16:49,095
Now, having made this step, this mistake of thinking that we are this body, we are this mind, etc., etc., which is your basic delusion, on the wheel of dependent origination, that's sankara.

130
00:16:49,956 --> 00:17:01,292
That's your dispositions, that's what it's created, a certain mode of dispositions around this essential mistake of thinking we are, for want of a better word, human beings.

131
00:17:03,517 --> 00:17:16,462
Now from that, of course, we form a relationship to the world whereby me is here and everything and every other is out there.

132
00:17:17,049 --> 00:17:20,554
Now this me and other become a separation.

133
00:17:20,674 --> 00:17:23,919
So this is what Buddhism means by a duality, living in a dual world.

134
00:17:24,799 --> 00:17:27,202
See, there's me here and everybody else out there.

135
00:17:27,844 --> 00:17:30,968
And me, I have things, so these are mine.

136
00:17:31,167 --> 00:17:34,051
As soon as I've created mine, I've created yours.

137
00:17:35,472 --> 00:17:39,919
Having created mine and yours, I live now in a very dualistic world.

138
00:17:41,012 --> 00:17:54,094
And the tighter I am about me, the closer I am about me, the more afraid I am about maintaining me, this, what might have been some sort of boundary, becomes more and more a barrier.

139
00:17:54,934 --> 00:17:55,936
See?

140
00:17:55,957 --> 00:17:59,263
So this differentiation between barrier and boundary.

141
00:17:59,964 --> 00:18:06,617
A river, for instance, might flow through a certain countryside, and on one side it might be green, and on the other side it might be desert.

142
00:18:07,440 --> 00:18:13,652
And what it's doing is it's creating a certain boundary, you might say, where there's a watershed on one side and none on the other.

143
00:18:14,729 --> 00:18:17,275
But it's quite possible that things can move across it.

144
00:18:18,157 --> 00:18:24,653
But when these two places become two countries, then this river suddenly becomes a barrier, and nobody can move from one place to the other.

145
00:18:26,157 --> 00:18:30,087
So what the me does, this ego...

146
00:18:30,372 --> 00:18:32,936
I don't particularly like using the word ego.

147
00:18:32,957 --> 00:18:33,679
It is used.

148
00:18:33,699 --> 00:18:39,369
The better word is the self, this sense of self that we have, this sense of self.

149
00:18:39,951 --> 00:18:45,162
What the self does is, of course, it demarcates very sharply.

150
00:18:45,241 --> 00:18:47,125
This is me, and that's not me.

151
00:18:47,507 --> 00:18:49,089
This is mine, and that's not mine.

152
00:18:50,942 --> 00:19:00,413
So now, once the self has got itself into that position, it now presumes itself to be more secure.

153
00:19:00,714 --> 00:19:06,981
Remember, fear is always the root emotion of self.

154
00:19:07,522 --> 00:19:10,185
Fear is right there at the base.

155
00:19:10,967 --> 00:19:13,109
It's prior to any other emotion.

156
00:19:13,130 --> 00:19:13,430
Why?

157
00:19:13,509 --> 00:19:17,575
Because the one thing that self is afraid of is its own death.

158
00:19:18,532 --> 00:19:21,215
That's why it's always trying to aggrandize itself.

159
00:19:21,355 --> 00:19:27,221
That's why it's always trying to sustain and trying to really make everything secure, batten things down.

160
00:19:29,064 --> 00:19:37,894
So this self now has a relationship to the world whereby it's going to feel more secure the bigger it is.

161
00:19:39,476 --> 00:19:44,681
The bigger house I've got, the bigger the pension, the bigger the car, I mean, you know, I feel better.

162
00:19:45,281 --> 00:19:45,402
Right?

163
00:19:46,411 --> 00:19:49,535
And the more things I've got, the more things I own, you see.

164
00:19:50,296 --> 00:19:54,182
So you can see how this aggrandizement slips into immorality.

165
00:19:54,563 --> 00:19:57,446
Because at some point, I'm up against other people.

166
00:19:58,528 --> 00:20:01,813
So I'm now into thieving and not doing my tax returns.

167
00:20:01,853 --> 00:20:06,259
Things like that, I try to fiddle, you know, just don't make...

168
00:20:09,125 --> 00:20:18,045
And how now you're into this area of aversion, of hatred, of pushing things away that you find are impinging upon your little bit of security.

169
00:20:18,526 --> 00:20:20,170
And how when it's too much, there's fear.

170
00:20:20,932 --> 00:20:21,413
You see?

171
00:20:22,422 --> 00:20:26,586
This goes right through, not only just material well-beings, but even our relationships.

172
00:20:26,807 --> 00:20:30,311
You know, my partner, my children.

173
00:20:30,332 --> 00:20:31,534
Do you see what I mean?

174
00:20:31,614 --> 00:20:34,017
And then you get this barrier turning up.

175
00:20:34,057 --> 00:20:42,587
And then you get working for your own family, for your own ethnic group, for your own nationality, for your own civilization.

176
00:20:42,607 --> 00:20:43,308
Do you see what I mean?

177
00:20:43,328 --> 00:20:44,951
It sort of grows out now like that.

178
00:20:45,191 --> 00:20:49,557
And of course, wherever it meets the other, that is your conflict.

179
00:20:50,218 --> 00:20:51,078
That is your war.

180
00:20:53,287 --> 00:20:58,596
So, what the Buddha discovered was this root cause, this root cause of self.

181
00:20:59,298 --> 00:21:00,759
You see, that's the point.

182
00:21:02,442 --> 00:21:15,025
Now, having discovered this root cause, this idea of a self, this feeling of a self, he now discovers that there are these three characteristics which symbolize the state of that self.

183
00:21:15,561 --> 00:21:18,248
Three fundamental, you might say, delusions.

184
00:21:18,749 --> 00:21:27,185
The first one is that although things, shall we say, change, actually I'm always the same.

185
00:21:27,926 --> 00:21:31,173
The self always seems to be the same self.

186
00:21:31,288 --> 00:21:36,616
I mean, I go to sleep and I wake up in the morning and I feel the same as I fell asleep.

187
00:21:37,597 --> 00:21:45,068
There's a feeling running through life that, okay, everything else changes a little bit, but I, me, inside me, I never change.

188
00:21:45,108 --> 00:21:48,453
I'm always the one person that I always thought I was.

189
00:21:50,054 --> 00:22:02,971
Now that, of course, is manifestly untrue, because when we actually look at what we mean by me, it turns out to be the personality, the character, my thinking, because these are all the things that the self says it is.

190
00:22:04,855 --> 00:22:17,833
But we know that we're not the same person that we were, say, at the age of two, when we looked at bugs and discovered this wonderful satipanya, this awareness wisdom, which we since forgot.

191
00:22:20,580 --> 00:22:25,806
And this same self now presumes itself to be solid.

192
00:22:27,387 --> 00:22:28,588
So it doesn't change.

193
00:22:28,608 --> 00:22:31,391
If it doesn't change, it must be solid, it must be substantial.

194
00:22:32,092 --> 00:22:35,915
So it somehow stands outside the world that we live in.

195
00:22:37,237 --> 00:22:38,577
So that's the self, you see.

196
00:22:38,837 --> 00:22:47,787
And these are the two characteristics, the two basic characteristics, that it doesn't change and that it's solid, it's immortal.

197
00:22:49,183 --> 00:23:00,920
When that is taken a step further up into our daily living, then we get this business of a relationship to what we experience.

198
00:23:00,940 --> 00:23:11,394
So that's when we get this business of wanting what makes me happy, what gives me pleasure, and not wanting what doesn't give me pleasure.

199
00:23:11,375 --> 00:23:13,720
So I'm now caught in a duality, right?

200
00:23:14,141 --> 00:23:21,655
If you just watch yourself in ordinary daily life, you'll see that there's this constant judging going on.

201
00:23:22,238 --> 00:23:24,603
Liking, disliking, wanting, not wanting.

202
00:23:24,643 --> 00:23:25,765
If I like it, I want it.

203
00:23:25,785 --> 00:23:27,428
If I don't like it, I don't want it.

204
00:23:28,309 --> 00:23:31,576
So the whole of life is just partitioned into these things.

205
00:23:31,557 --> 00:23:34,160
If I like the person, then we can meet for coffee.

206
00:23:34,180 --> 00:23:37,483
If I don't like them, I don't want to see them.

207
00:23:37,503 --> 00:23:43,951
So this constant shifting of life according to these two different colours, the dark and the bright.

208
00:23:44,451 --> 00:23:48,717
So these are your three characteristics.

209
00:23:48,737 --> 00:23:56,906
You can call them existential characteristics because they are fundamental to this whole idea of what is the meaning of our existence.

210
00:23:58,304 --> 00:24:07,095
So, again, what is the purpose of our meditation, in a sense, from the point of view of what is it we're actually trying to see?

211
00:24:07,355 --> 00:24:09,999
Well, we're trying to see these three things.

212
00:24:10,799 --> 00:24:25,459
Because in seeing these three things clearly, and seeing that they are false, that brings about the liberation of that very consciousness, which is identified with everything it did think was permanent and substantial.

213
00:24:26,451 --> 00:24:31,655
So our viewpoint of whatever comes up is always coming from these three angles.

214
00:24:33,657 --> 00:24:37,741
So for instance, when I'm sitting here, you see, all these hindrances come up.

215
00:24:39,343 --> 00:24:45,087
So the first one may be something like, you know, I've been planning to go on a holiday somewhere.

216
00:24:46,048 --> 00:24:50,231
So I've come on this weekend retreat and all I can think about is this holiday I'm planning.

217
00:24:51,473 --> 00:24:51,594
Right?

218
00:24:51,614 --> 00:24:55,497
Because that's what's uppermost in my mind and that's what I'm really going to enjoy.

219
00:24:55,779 --> 00:25:00,164
and I've got all these ideas of what I want to do and where I want to go and all this sort of stuff.

220
00:25:00,704 --> 00:25:09,855
So I'm sitting here and it's quite natural because I want to do this, the mind will now be incredibly inventive and give you all sorts of wonderful ideas.

221
00:25:11,036 --> 00:25:14,400
So what we want to do is we want to discover what's empowering this?

222
00:25:14,460 --> 00:25:15,540
Why can't I just stop it?

223
00:25:16,382 --> 00:25:21,448
Why can't I just say, well this weekend I'll put it to the side and I won't think about this anymore.

224
00:25:21,468 --> 00:25:23,609
Why can't we do it?

225
00:25:24,333 --> 00:25:32,415
Coming to terms with the fact that we're not actually in control of the mind is a bit of an eye-opener.

226
00:25:32,435 --> 00:25:37,971
Whereas we thought it was me thinking, actually it's thinking, and I'm swamped by it.

227
00:25:39,335 --> 00:25:41,137
There are occasions when I can use it.

228
00:25:41,759 --> 00:25:46,106
I mean, like, for instance, if I go on holiday, I have to use it for planning.

229
00:25:46,188 --> 00:25:47,569
I've got to phone people up.

230
00:25:47,589 --> 00:25:50,335
I've got to set up hotels and et cetera, et cetera.

231
00:25:50,695 --> 00:25:52,378
So this is a correct use, you see.

232
00:25:52,759 --> 00:25:57,428
But overlaying that are all these dreams about what we're going to do, how it's going to be.

233
00:25:57,829 --> 00:26:01,775
And that's where the wishing is coming, that's where the wanting is coming.

234
00:26:02,435 --> 00:26:15,352
And once we've begun to build, shall we say, an atmosphere, a conditioning in the mind of seeking pleasure in a holiday, seeking happiness in a holiday, then of course it'll carry on.

235
00:26:16,212 --> 00:26:20,377
So here we come to a meditation and suddenly we can't stop thinking about it.

236
00:26:21,403 --> 00:26:22,726
It's completely flooded us.

237
00:26:23,727 --> 00:26:31,836
So now, what we've come to realize is that by empowering a certain conditioning, we give it its own life.

238
00:26:32,857 --> 00:26:38,765
And the only thing we can do once we've set something in motion is wait for that momentum to die out.

239
00:26:39,405 --> 00:26:42,210
Exactly the same in a way as you drive a car.

240
00:26:42,930 --> 00:26:46,634
You can stomp on the brakes as hard as you want, but it's still going to move forward.

241
00:26:48,303 --> 00:26:53,731
So, in our meditation here, if we try and stomp on this stuff, what is it we're stomping on?

242
00:26:53,792 --> 00:26:55,561
What is it we're trying to put the brakes on?

243
00:26:56,740 --> 00:26:58,863
Now that, you can see, is a suppressive measure.

244
00:26:59,663 --> 00:27:11,803
So it's no good if we're full of this desire and the mind's just full of thinking, full of thinking, full of thinking, to sort of get hard with it and smack it on and sort of get rigid and start watching the breath come what may.

245
00:27:12,243 --> 00:27:13,625
Because that's just putting the brakes on.

246
00:27:13,645 --> 00:27:18,133
All we're going to do is create even more turbulence, more bad energy within the system.

247
00:27:18,993 --> 00:27:24,402
So all we can do is recognize that here is the conditioning I've set up

248
00:27:25,698 --> 00:27:27,621
Because only me can govern the mind.

249
00:27:27,740 --> 00:27:31,606
Because only me can put ideas into the mind and empower those ideas.

250
00:27:32,086 --> 00:27:36,413
So here I am in this enormous desire, and what can I do?

251
00:27:36,473 --> 00:27:44,905
So every time I wake up, I just have to recognize, ah, desire, holiday, desiring, desiring.

252
00:27:45,207 --> 00:27:46,489
Then I come back.

253
00:27:46,548 --> 00:27:47,710
Now I have two choices.

254
00:27:48,431 --> 00:27:50,253
I can either come back to the breath,

255
00:27:50,825 --> 00:27:58,634
Or I can, as it were, search for the excitement in the body, that sense of wanting to enjoy myself.

256
00:27:59,694 --> 00:28:07,262
Now, if I go back to the breath, even though I do it gently, in a way, that's also a very gentle suppression.

257
00:28:07,463 --> 00:28:11,188
I've acknowledged it as it is, but I'm still not looking at the root cause.

258
00:28:11,848 --> 00:28:14,010
Now, many a time, the mind is just restless.

259
00:28:14,551 --> 00:28:19,396
And often, you'll find that just by guiding the mind back to the breath, it'll just bring a sense of peace.

260
00:28:20,473 --> 00:28:26,301
But when it's very strong, then you've really got to go underneath it to find out what the emotion is that's empowering it.

261
00:28:27,643 --> 00:28:31,909
So dropping into the body, one feels that excitement, you see.

262
00:28:31,949 --> 00:28:42,162
Staying with that excitement at the feeling level means that, A, it isn't going to slip up into these higher faculties and create further dreams.

263
00:28:43,103 --> 00:28:49,471
And B, just by watching it here, because it can't do this, it'll just begin to slowly die out.

264
00:28:50,373 --> 00:28:55,599
And the time it takes to die out is a measure of how much we've empowered it.

265
00:28:56,181 --> 00:29:00,788
So if it's going to take a couple of hours, it takes a couple of hours.

266
00:29:00,807 --> 00:29:02,670
If it's going to take a couple of weeks, it's going to take a couple of weeks.

267
00:29:02,809 --> 00:29:04,031
There's not much you can do about it.

268
00:29:05,917 --> 00:29:16,510
Now, whenever the mind wanders off like that, even though it hasn't been a conscious decision on our part, there has been a moment of empowerment.

269
00:29:16,852 --> 00:29:22,898
This is known in Buddhist psychology as habitual, an habitual act of will.

270
00:29:23,599 --> 00:29:27,325
So there's many things in life that we just do as an habitual act of will.

271
00:29:27,726 --> 00:29:29,227
You just catch yourself doing something.

272
00:29:29,647 --> 00:29:34,473
I mean, often, even before you know it, an idea for tea's come in your head, and before you know it, you're drinking it.

273
00:29:35,212 --> 00:29:37,757
So it's just been empowered naturally as a habit.

274
00:29:38,218 --> 00:29:39,119
That's what a habit is.

275
00:29:40,962 --> 00:29:53,002
So now, recognizing that there has been an act of will in there, you see, we're even sharper, as it were, to wake up out of that fantasy and to recognize what's happened.

276
00:29:53,522 --> 00:29:57,548
Now, the thing about an habitual act of will is that it will just keep the wheel rolling.

277
00:29:58,048 --> 00:30:01,173
It won't actually make it that much worse.

278
00:30:02,154 --> 00:30:10,567
It's only if you were to stop here and say, well, I've come on this retreat, but really, what I really want to do is think about Machu Picchu and Antigua.

279
00:30:11,067 --> 00:30:12,430
So you sit here, and that's what you do.

280
00:30:12,690 --> 00:30:13,832
Well, of course, you're off then.

281
00:30:13,892 --> 00:30:15,513
You've written a book.

282
00:30:18,515 --> 00:30:32,750
Now, every time you wake up out of that and you notice, ah, dreaming, dreaming, okay, and you come back, and you come back either to the breath or to the emotion, you see, now that is an act of will, a conscious act of will.

283
00:30:33,691 --> 00:30:35,452
That's an empowering act of will.

284
00:30:35,752 --> 00:30:42,180
That's beginning to develop a new attitude, a new habit of being in the present.

285
00:30:44,582 --> 00:30:48,066
So there's your practice with desire, with anything which attracts us.

286
00:30:55,640 --> 00:31:06,089
When it comes to the second hindrance, aversion, all the little grudges and hatreds and irritations which also do very much the same thing, it's exactly the same technique.

287
00:31:06,971 --> 00:31:10,914
You have to observe what it is, you have to recognize, acknowledge what it is.

288
00:31:11,454 --> 00:31:13,356
That's irritation, you see.

289
00:31:14,258 --> 00:31:21,984
And then again, if it's something small, something silly, perhaps you can come back to the breath and it will just, as it were, die out because it's not being empowered.

290
00:31:22,588 --> 00:31:34,541
But if it's very strong, then you may have to go into the body, as it were, and search the feeling of anger, search and feel the irritation, the grudge, the unforgivingness, whatever's there that's causing it.

291
00:31:35,064 --> 00:31:38,353
And you have to stay there, you see, you have to wait for it to burn out.

292
00:31:38,839 --> 00:31:40,321
which isn't sometimes very pleasant.

293
00:31:41,983 --> 00:31:49,512
Now, when you get there, you've got to recognize the feeling of not wanting to actually experience these things.

294
00:31:49,933 --> 00:31:51,675
So there's your aversion.

295
00:31:52,297 --> 00:32:03,771
This aversion is actually what's not allowing that bad feeling, that anger to die out, because we like, we enjoy expressing anger.

296
00:32:04,372 --> 00:32:04,752
Correct?

297
00:32:05,634 --> 00:32:06,535
It's a relief, isn't it?

298
00:32:07,612 --> 00:32:21,428
But with the relief of anger, with the relief of kicking the dog or something, there is a development of that particular way of thinking, that particular way of feeling.

299
00:32:22,409 --> 00:32:25,071
So we're actually saying, it's right for me to get angry.

300
00:32:27,894 --> 00:32:33,261
So we have to come back on that and we have to notice this relationship we have with anger, with cruelty.

301
00:32:33,622 --> 00:32:36,285
Cruelty is a delicious thing.

302
00:32:37,092 --> 00:32:40,356
the torture against job satisfaction.

303
00:32:40,978 --> 00:32:41,337
Correct?

304
00:32:42,400 --> 00:32:44,102
Definitely.

305
00:32:44,122 --> 00:32:46,925
Because he wouldn't do it, huh?

306
00:32:48,067 --> 00:32:50,230
So that's this whole business of aversion.

307
00:32:50,590 --> 00:32:52,193
In aversion, of course, there's boredom.

308
00:32:52,513 --> 00:32:55,699
So boredom can be a real bane for meditators.

309
00:32:57,000 --> 00:33:00,486
And what you've really got to ask yourself about boredom is, where's it coming from, you see?

310
00:33:00,605 --> 00:33:01,768
What's the root of boredom?

311
00:33:04,250 --> 00:33:05,512
It's expectancy, isn't it?

312
00:33:05,797 --> 00:33:07,279
We expect something exciting.

313
00:33:07,319 --> 00:33:08,461
We expect something to happen.

314
00:33:08,481 --> 00:33:12,147
We expect some great, wonderful thing and nothing's happening.

315
00:33:12,167 --> 00:33:12,648
We get bored.

316
00:33:13,250 --> 00:33:14,112
I'm just watching the breath.

317
00:33:14,172 --> 00:33:14,913
I mean, what the hell?

318
00:33:16,435 --> 00:33:17,057
Really boring.

319
00:33:18,779 --> 00:33:18,980
See?

320
00:33:19,320 --> 00:33:24,410
So again, you have to be very careful because what boredom will tell us to do is to seek distraction.

321
00:33:25,451 --> 00:33:28,277
So you're watching the breath here and you think, I'll watch it here.

322
00:33:28,257 --> 00:33:29,719
And then you watch it, yeah, boredom.

323
00:33:29,739 --> 00:33:30,760
I'll do a mantra.

324
00:33:30,840 --> 00:33:33,204
And then they're all fed up with that.

325
00:33:33,224 --> 00:33:33,965
I'm going to do some walking.

326
00:33:35,327 --> 00:33:38,753
Before you know it, you're just being swung around by this boredom.

327
00:33:39,454 --> 00:33:42,058
So the last thing you do with boredom is seek distraction.

328
00:33:42,179 --> 00:33:44,583
You just keep going back and you feel the boredom.

329
00:33:44,623 --> 00:33:45,365
It's an aversion.

330
00:33:45,525 --> 00:33:46,185
It's a dislike.

331
00:33:46,946 --> 00:33:47,548
Hatred, you see.

332
00:33:48,930 --> 00:33:51,994
And again, you always notice your relationship to boredom.

333
00:33:52,055 --> 00:33:53,617
How you don't want to feel it.

334
00:33:54,680 --> 00:33:55,580
Don't want to feel it.

335
00:33:59,375 --> 00:34:06,163
The next two can be pretty heavy too, the sloth and torpor, especially on the first day of a retreat, first couple of days actually.

336
00:34:07,223 --> 00:34:15,434
I must say that those of you who have only experienced a sort of one day, two day or three day retreat probably don't realise that it actually does get better.

337
00:34:18,717 --> 00:34:21,501
Things do lift and you do get a clarity and

338
00:34:22,054 --> 00:34:31,255
for the first three days I mean you're getting rid of all the stuff you brought with us you see so it can be quite difficult and also trying to lift the energy um

339
00:34:33,056 --> 00:34:41,085
Even when we live a very sort of fast, pacey life, it's actually mixed in with things like anxiety and stress and stuff.

340
00:34:42,266 --> 00:34:44,208
And that's not a good energy.

341
00:34:44,789 --> 00:34:51,657
So when you come here, when you come to a retreat like this, of course, because there's nothing to do, see what happens to all that energy?

342
00:34:52,619 --> 00:34:54,059
You don't know where to go.

343
00:34:54,079 --> 00:34:56,081
So it just collapses into itself.

344
00:34:56,302 --> 00:35:00,347
You just feel this exhaustion, this sort of restless boredom, this...

345
00:35:00,327 --> 00:35:03,114
restless exhaustion, you know.

346
00:35:05,161 --> 00:35:12,041
So the first three days of any course that you go on, of this nature anyway, are always brutal.

347
00:35:16,527 --> 00:35:22,353
So sloth and torpor, they refer to just two different states of feeling down.

348
00:35:22,913 --> 00:35:24,394
One is the physical tiredness.

349
00:35:24,914 --> 00:35:27,538
One is the sort of mental cloud that you can get into.

350
00:35:27,577 --> 00:35:30,320
And sometimes they both come together.

351
00:35:31,362 --> 00:35:34,804
In fact, they mostly come together.

352
00:35:34,826 --> 00:35:36,286
Sometimes you can feel the one and not the other.

353
00:35:36,306 --> 00:35:39,070
You can be fairly clear in the head, but you just feel down.

354
00:35:39,269 --> 00:35:43,693
Now, again, you don't do what the hindrance tells you.

355
00:35:44,414 --> 00:35:46,197
The hindrance says, have a kip.

356
00:35:47,222 --> 00:36:14,327
you know 10 minutes you feel great you see but in fact you go to sleep and that's the end of it you know because what you're doing is you're piling more energy pushing down you see using sleep as a sort as a suppressive yeah remember we taught that early on as kids you know if we get a bit naughty then so it's because they're tired you know put the bed and then you and then you wake up all right and you think oh yeah if i feel bad i go to bed

357
00:36:16,518 --> 00:36:36,619
And of course depressives, people who are depressed and especially those who have depression as illness, so much of their time is just going to sleep, just falling asleep because of this awful heaviness and they haven't got the will, they haven't got perhaps a reason to sort of lift themselves up against it.

358
00:36:40,193 --> 00:36:44,637
So the thing to do when you feel slothful or tired is to do the opposite.

359
00:36:44,998 --> 00:36:47,460
You know, you put energy into the posture, you open your eyes.

360
00:36:47,521 --> 00:36:49,762
If you feel that that's not good enough, do some standing.

361
00:36:50,103 --> 00:36:51,925
See, stand up.

362
00:36:51,945 --> 00:36:52,425
See?

363
00:36:52,445 --> 00:36:53,847
Just refuse to be annihilated.

364
00:36:57,590 --> 00:37:09,103
And that's why it is important during the day to get every walking period, get a good 10, 20 minutes of fast walking because there is a connection between the body and these sorts of feelings too, you know.

365
00:37:14,398 --> 00:37:16,992
The next one is the opposite of that, a sense of restlessness.

366
00:37:17,092 --> 00:37:21,355
Now for me, the way I experience it, is that the one is the other, one's going in,

367
00:37:21,907 --> 00:37:22,889
And one's coming out.

368
00:37:23,911 --> 00:37:26,835
Now restlessness, of course, tells you to get up and do things.

369
00:37:27,335 --> 00:37:27,976
Don't hang about.

370
00:37:28,898 --> 00:37:30,039
Don't just sit there and do something.

371
00:37:32,003 --> 00:37:34,246
So again, you do the opposite.

372
00:37:34,266 --> 00:37:40,757
You sit very still, you don't move, and you just try and get in touch with that feeling of wanting to move, wanting to go.

373
00:37:41,157 --> 00:37:44,202
Often, of course, it begins to express itself in these fantasies.

374
00:37:44,782 --> 00:37:48,068
So in which case you've got to work with those desires.

375
00:37:48,047 --> 00:37:53,873
But sometimes it can be just almost a pure restlessness, just a feeling of fidgetiness, you see.

376
00:37:54,213 --> 00:37:58,137
So the more you relax around that, the more you sort of relax the body.

377
00:37:58,177 --> 00:38:02,501
Remember the posture, in the posture the energy is just coming up the spine.

378
00:38:03,202 --> 00:38:05,144
That's all the energy you need to become enlightened.

379
00:38:05,164 --> 00:38:10,250
If you could sit like that and maintain your mindfulness, the Buddha says, for seven days, you'd probably make it.

380
00:38:10,971 --> 00:38:13,733
Either that or what we call the non-returner.

381
00:38:14,233 --> 00:38:18,038
So, you know, it's worth getting the posture right, eh?

382
00:38:18,018 --> 00:38:27,110
So, you're lifting the energy up the spine, see, it's straight up the spine, and then with the out-breath, you can imagine it coming down into the abdomen, the hara.

383
00:38:27,130 --> 00:38:30,335
See, this is where the will is based.

384
00:38:31,315 --> 00:38:41,409
So, whenever there's frazzleness, whenever the body feels, you know, restless, just lift the spine up, you see, draw the energy with the in-breath up the spine, with the out-breath down the body.

385
00:38:41,389 --> 00:38:44,956
and relax around it, you see, and you'll feel that restlessness.

386
00:38:45,115 --> 00:38:51,346
But because it's got nowhere to hold on to, you see, eventually it'll just collapse, it'll just turn.

387
00:38:51,365 --> 00:38:55,833
And this is true, you know, if you feel restless before you sleep.

388
00:38:57,635 --> 00:39:06,570
One of the good tricks to go to sleep if you feel very restless is to take a position where you are comfortable, then refuse to move.

389
00:39:06,668 --> 00:39:07,648
You don't move at all.

390
00:39:08,911 --> 00:39:11,434
And then you'll see, it'll be a battle for a little while.

391
00:39:13,197 --> 00:39:15,039
Nobody wants to move around and do this.

392
00:39:15,260 --> 00:39:17,264
And then suddenly it'll just flip and that's it.

393
00:39:17,824 --> 00:39:20,327
Because it's got nowhere to go, so it just burns itself out.

394
00:39:20,449 --> 00:39:24,795
But as soon as you turn over, as soon as you get up from the posture, you've empowered it.

395
00:39:25,635 --> 00:39:40,757
It feels good, you know, like the sorts of uncomfortable feeling of restlessness disappear when you move, but the restlessness as a way in which turbulent energy is expressing itself is simply being re-empowered.

396
00:39:41,798 --> 00:39:42,099
Do you see?

397
00:39:43,260 --> 00:39:54,597
So the more we can suffer this stuff, the more we can burn, the more we can allow ourselves to sit in the midst of these flames, the quicker all these hindrances begin to die out for us.

398
00:39:57,800 --> 00:40:01,425
The other one which is linked in with restlessness is guilt, remorse.

399
00:40:02,306 --> 00:40:05,851
All that to do with what happens when we do something which is harmful.

400
00:40:06,914 --> 00:40:09,297
And that you can see, because that makes you fidgety, doesn't it?

401
00:40:09,958 --> 00:40:11,460
Guilt makes you jump a bit.

402
00:40:12,362 --> 00:40:14,045
So again, it's very much the same thing.

403
00:40:14,224 --> 00:40:19,492
When guilt feelings come up, remorse feelings come up, all those feelings, it's the very same thing.

404
00:40:19,673 --> 00:40:24,380
One acknowledges them, one stops the dreaming, one goes into the feeling.

405
00:40:25,103 --> 00:40:31,400
One goes into the feeling, one suffers the consequences of one's unwholesome actions.

406
00:40:32,949 --> 00:40:35,213
There's no need for punishment in Buddhism.

407
00:40:35,233 --> 00:40:38,737
You just have to suffer the consequences of your actions.

408
00:40:39,117 --> 00:40:41,780
There's no need to judge ourselves as evil or bad.

409
00:40:42,061 --> 00:40:43,903
There's no need to give ourselves extra punishment.

410
00:40:44,804 --> 00:40:46,367
You don't have to give yourself up to the police.

411
00:40:46,967 --> 00:40:47,527
Isn't that a relief?

412
00:40:48,088 --> 00:40:58,722
You can just sit there and the very pain of coming to terms with these things is the consequence and the healing.

413
00:40:58,742 --> 00:41:02,045
It's very interesting because I read a little article on, if you remember...

414
00:41:02,025 --> 00:41:08,195
In England we had that terrible Norse murder with Brady and Myra Hindley.

415
00:41:08,215 --> 00:41:12,661
And he's written a book, it seems, about serial killers, and it's meant to be a very insightful book.

416
00:41:13,143 --> 00:41:21,215
And the person who helped him write it says in the article that he asked him, did he ever think about the suffering of his victims?

417
00:41:21,976 --> 00:41:23,278
And his answer is very telling.

418
00:41:23,438 --> 00:41:26,202
He said, if I thought about the suffering of my victims, I'd go mad.

419
00:41:28,206 --> 00:41:29,467
So it's in him, you see.

420
00:41:30,123 --> 00:41:32,931
You can't hurt anybody out there without hurting yourself.

421
00:41:34,938 --> 00:41:38,608
Very interesting that, I thought.

422
00:41:38,628 --> 00:41:41,719
And the final one is doubt.

423
00:41:44,112 --> 00:41:47,356
The Buddha asks us not to believe anything that he says.

424
00:41:47,635 --> 00:41:53,121
It's not a faith religion in that sense, because it's about knowledge, it's about understanding.

425
00:41:54,063 --> 00:41:55,264
And faith grows.

426
00:41:55,304 --> 00:41:57,706
Faith is an intellectual ascent.

427
00:41:58,447 --> 00:42:05,094
It's a confidence we put into the teaching of the Buddha by way of listening, which makes sense to us.

428
00:42:05,554 --> 00:42:11,621
So, you know, we hear the teaching, it makes sense to us, and then we go away and we think about it ourselves, and we do a bit of practice,

429
00:42:11,601 --> 00:42:14,726
and the confidence comes to sort of give the practice a go.

430
00:42:14,766 --> 00:42:31,467
When the practice begins to yield results, then of course you tend to get more confidence in the practice, and so it rolls on until it is said when a person glimpses, has that glimpse of nibbana, the sotapanna, the stream entrant, as they're called.

431
00:42:32,047 --> 00:42:36,393
Once that happens, of course they know now that there is an end to suffering.

432
00:42:36,373 --> 00:42:40,280
Even if it's only a glimpse, the Buddha says it's like a flash of lightning, as quick as that.

433
00:42:40,519 --> 00:42:48,452
But at least within that person there is this real knowledge of the end of suffering, at which point faith now becomes rock hard.

434
00:42:48,492 --> 00:42:50,155
It can't be disturbed.

435
00:42:51,376 --> 00:42:56,364
But until that point happens to us, then there will always be some doubts floating around.

436
00:42:57,025 --> 00:43:03,815
And doubt, of course, stops you committing yourself, and therefore you don't do the practice.

437
00:43:04,032 --> 00:43:06,215
And there's three areas usually of doubt.

438
00:43:06,335 --> 00:43:12,702
First of all, in the actual teaching itself, that it's not going to deliver.

439
00:43:12,742 --> 00:43:15,766
There's doubt in the teacher, of course.

440
00:43:16,347 --> 00:43:18,090
Don't look at me like that.

441
00:43:18,951 --> 00:43:21,715
But the big one, of course, is usually doubting oneself.

442
00:43:21,914 --> 00:43:23,838
Everybody else can do it, but I can't.

443
00:43:24,318 --> 00:43:27,222
And that's often a big one for a lot of meditators.

444
00:43:27,202 --> 00:43:32,568
They have a certain ground faith in the teaching and they see how it works.

445
00:43:33,590 --> 00:43:41,561
And they usually have a certain faith in whatever teachers they meet, but they're usually about themselves saying, I can't do it, you see.

446
00:43:42,101 --> 00:43:44,724
So doubt is pernicious.

447
00:43:44,766 --> 00:43:46,487
You have to be very careful with doubt.

448
00:43:46,588 --> 00:43:49,632
It can really destroy your spiritual life.

449
00:43:49,612 --> 00:43:59,003
So whenever doubt comes up, you have to really turn on it, you see, and feel the doubt and really not do what it says, you see.

450
00:43:59,523 --> 00:44:03,047
Very careful about that sort of self-judgment, very undermining.

451
00:44:04,050 --> 00:44:07,132
That's not only, is it, in the spiritual life, it's anything, isn't it?

452
00:44:07,653 --> 00:44:10,818
I mean, if you start a job and you doubt you can do it, you won't be able to do it.

453
00:44:11,358 --> 00:44:12,480
You just undermine yourself.

454
00:44:14,670 --> 00:44:21,201
So whenever doubt comes up, you always have to make that leap of faith, you see, yes I can.

455
00:44:21,221 --> 00:44:22,443
Do you see what I mean?

456
00:44:22,603 --> 00:44:25,407
To hell with it, you know, yes I can, you see.

457
00:44:28,271 --> 00:44:32,577
So beware of doubt if you do suffer from it a lot.

458
00:44:32,597 --> 00:44:34,940
Some people do, some people don't, you know.

459
00:44:34,920 --> 00:44:37,867
These hindrances vary from people to people.

460
00:44:38,447 --> 00:44:44,940
Everybody has their own little constellation of horror which they have to work out.

461
00:44:45,702 --> 00:44:47,126
That's our karma, you see.

462
00:44:54,420 --> 00:44:55,983
So...

463
00:44:58,715 --> 00:45:02,318
I hope that's given you some sort of pointers when it comes to the hindrances.

464
00:45:03,340 --> 00:45:12,791
The last thing, of course, to say is what happens when we feel peaceful and wonderful and we feel that everything's going perfectly well?

465
00:45:13,532 --> 00:45:15,494
Well, don't rest on our laurels.

466
00:45:15,574 --> 00:45:16,556
That's the big thing.

467
00:45:16,577 --> 00:45:22,143
You don't sort of say, ah, finally a bit of peace, and you sink into the peace and you're just indulging peace now.

468
00:45:22,583 --> 00:45:24,545
So when it goes, you get really frustrated.

469
00:45:25,246 --> 00:45:27,809
Why can't I be peaceful like I was yesterday?

470
00:45:28,246 --> 00:45:36,681
So when there's a calmness comes, when there's a certain clarity comes, when the meditation is, as we would say, it is good, right?

471
00:45:37,003 --> 00:45:45,679
In fact, remember, in terms of the process of enlightenment, even should we spend a whole hour just coming off these thoughts, that's good meditation.

472
00:45:45,860 --> 00:45:47,503
That's the practice.

473
00:45:47,838 --> 00:45:55,090
But even so, there are times when there seems a certain concentration comes, a clarity, a quietness, a stillness and all that, you see.

474
00:45:55,451 --> 00:46:00,298
Well then, you see, really use that to begin to penetrate the breath, you see.

475
00:46:00,840 --> 00:46:02,182
Because that's what you're left with.

476
00:46:02,222 --> 00:46:04,246
There's not much else when you're completely quiet.

477
00:46:04,405 --> 00:46:08,293
The only thing that's going on tends to be the very subtle movement of breath.

478
00:46:09,420 --> 00:46:23,302
So you go into that and you're looking at it very closely, very intently, trying to see the exact beginning of the in-breath, the exact ending of it, the exact beginning of the out-breath, the exact ending of it.

479
00:46:24,103 --> 00:46:29,791
And where you're driving that consciousness is to the point where mind contacts matter.

480
00:46:29,771 --> 00:46:40,967
And it's right there that we can see especially these qualities of transience, impermanence, rising and falling, and the insubstantiality, this not-self.

481
00:46:41,068 --> 00:46:42,590
That's when it becomes very apparent.

482
00:46:43,371 --> 00:46:50,942
Now, such is our state of delusion, such is our ignorance, that it just isn't good enough to see it once.

483
00:46:50,961 --> 00:46:57,231
You've got to really keep seeing it and seeing it and seeing it, and very slowly the penny drops.

484
00:46:58,222 --> 00:47:05,052
Only occasionally does a person have one of these blowout Kenshos or Satoris, you know.

485
00:47:05,074 --> 00:47:14,527
The normal progress, normal spiritual progress is just this wearing away, you know, this sort of Chinese drip.

486
00:47:14,507 --> 00:47:20,110
And slowly we begin to perceive, slowly begins to turn the way we see things.

487
00:47:20,813 --> 00:47:26,052
And in turning the way we see things, the personality begins to change, the relationships begin to change.

488
00:47:27,277 --> 00:47:30,811
So it's a very, for most of us, a very slow process.

